      "id": "GENUS_PHALACROCORAX",
      "name": "Phalacrocorax",
      "rank": "GENUS",
      "description": "Great cormorants and shags — large, fish-eating waterbirds whose distinctive habit of spreading their wings to dry after diving is one of the most familiar sights at coasts and inland waters worldwide. Cormorants lack the fully waterproofed plumage of ducks and grebes, instead using partially water-permeable feathers that reduce buoyancy and help them pursue fish at depth — but require post-dive drying. This genus includes the most widespread and familiar cormorant species found across every continent except South America, ranging from the world's largest cormorant colony to species restricted to single island groups.",
